\begin_layout Subsection
Device ID Numbers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All EVGs and EVRs in an IOC are identified by an integer number.
 This number is first given in the IOC shell functions described below,
 and repeated in the INP or OUT field of all database records which reference
 it.
 Both EVGs, and EVRs share the same namespace.
 So it is not possible to have EVG 1 and EVR 1 in the same IOC.
 This restriction is needed since some code is shared between these two
 devices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
VME64x Device Configuration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The VME bus based EVRs and EVGs are configured using one of the following
 IOC shell functions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset listings
lstparams "language=bash"
inline false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

# Generator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

mrmEvgSetupVME(10,5,0x20000000,3,0x26)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

# Receiver
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

mrmEvrSetupVME(1,3,0x30000000,4,0x28)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this example EVR #1 is defined to be the VME card in slot 5.
 It is given the A32 base address of 0x20000000 and configured to interrupt
 on level 3 with vector 0x26.
 EVG #10 is then defined as the card in slot 3.
\end_layout

